05580nam a22008535i 9783110685633DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106856337 a10.1515/97831106856332doi  a(DE-B1597)540082  a(OCoLC)1149395864  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE0483pa880qDE-1011 aScapin, Nuria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Flower of Suffering :bTheology, Justice, and the Cosmos in Aeschylus’ ›Oresteia‹ and Presocratic Thought /cNuria Scapin. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XII, 264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Classics - Supplementary Volumes ,x1868-4785 ;v97  aDiss. cniv. of St Andrewsd2016.00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t0. Introduction -- tPart I: Philosophical Theology in Presocratic Philosophy and the Oresteia -- t1. Explicit Theological Innovations: Xenophanes’ God -- t2. God and the Unity of Opposites: Heraclitus -- t3. Zeus Whoever He Is -- t4. Zeus as the Ultimate Principle behind Reality -- tPart II: Cosmic Justice: between a Metaphysics of Harmony and a Metaphysics of Conflict -- t5. Cosmic Justice and the Metaphysics of Opposites: Anaximander, Heraclitus, and Parmenides -- t6. Dikê, Time, and Necessity in the Oresteia -- t7. Dikê as conflict in the Oresteia -- t8. Persuasive Dikê: from violence to kindness -- t9. A Cosmos of Opposites -- t10. Epilogue -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Sources0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGreek tragedy occupies a prominent place in the development of early Greek thought. However, even within the partial renaissance of debates about tragedy’s roots in the popular thought of archaic Greece, its potential connection to the early philosophical tradition remains, with few exceptions, at the periphery of current interest. This book aims to show that our understanding of Aeschylus’ Oresteia is enhanced by seeing that the trilogy’s treatment of Zeus and Justice (Dikê) shares certain concepts, assumptions, categories of thought, and forms of expression with the surviving fragments and doxography of certain Presocratic thinkers (especially Anaximander, Xenophanes, Heraclitus, and Parmenides). By examining several aspects of the tragic trilogy in relation to Presocratic debates about theology and cosmic justice, it shows how such scrutiny may affect our understanding of the theological ‘tension’ and metaphysical assumptions underpinning the Oresteia’s dramatic narrative. Ultimately, it argues that Aeschylus bestows on the experience of human suffering, as it is given in the contradictory multiplicity of the world, the status of a profound form of knowledge: a meeting point between the human and divine spheres.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023)  aAeschylus.  aGreek tragedy.  aPresocratic philosophy.  athe Oresteia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2020 Englishz978311070483908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2020z9783110704631oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831106857630 cprintz978311068552740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783